#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:7
msgid "Sharing Work on a Ticket"
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:9
msgid ""
"When a ticket is complex enough, it may require attention from more than "
"one agent (or even more than one department!)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:13
msgid ""
"In these cases, the simplest thing to do is usually just to **take turns "
"working on the ticket**. (:doc:`Splitting tickets </advanced/ticket-"
"actions/split>` is another option, best reserved for when a ticket really"
" encompasses multiple problems, or when taking turns would needlessly "
"block one agent’s progress.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:23
msgid ""
"Reassign a ticket (via the *Group* and *Owner* settings) to let "
"colleagues know you’re done with your part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:27
msgid "How it works"
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:29
msgid ""
"Suppose a call comes into the sales department. A sales rep takes the "
"call, creates a ticket, and looks up some prices for the customer. After "
"recording his notes, the rep then decides that this ticket needs to be "
"passed onto customer service."
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:35
msgid ""
"Our sales rep can simply un-assign himself has the **owner** of the "
"ticket and re-assign the ticket to the Customer Service **group**. *All "
"customer service agents will be notified of the incoming ticket*, and the"
" first available agent can assign herself to pick up where the sales rep "
"left off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../advanced/suggested-workflows.rst:41
msgid ""
"Be sure to leave notes with as much information as possible for the next "
"agent!"
msgstr ""

